ssive faith-based racial justice advocates kept up the fight even as media attention shifted elsewhere.Wuthnow tells the stories of the faith-based affordable housing project in St. Louis that sparked controversy in the Nixon White House; a pastor’s lawsuit in North Carolina that launched the nation’s first busing program for school desegregation; the faith outreach initiative for Barack Obama’s presidential campaign; and church-mobilized protests following the deaths of Trayvon Martin, Freddie Gray, and George Floyd. Drawing on extensive materials on denominations, journalists, and social scientists, Wuthnow offers a detailed and frank discussion of both the achievements and the limitations of faith leaders’ roles. He focuses on different issues that emerged at different times, tracing the efforts of Black and White faith leaders who sometimes worked cooperatively and more often tackled problems in complementary ways. Taken together, these stories provide lessons in what faith communities have done and how they can better advocate for racial justice in the years ahead.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivil rights leaderszUnited States. 0aCivil rightsxReligious aspectszUnited States. 0aCivil rightszUnited StatesxReligious aspects. 0aRacial justicezUnited States. 0aReligious leaderszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh  aAffirmative Action.  aAffordable Housing.  aBlack justice.  aBlack.  aBusing.  aChurches.  aCivil Rights.  aCommunity Development.  aCongregations.  aCriminal Justice.  aFaith Communities and the Fight for Racial Justice: What Has Worked, What Hasn't, and Lessons We Can Learn.  aFaith.  aJustice.  aMultiracial Ministry.  aObama.  aPrinceton University Press.  aPrinceton.  aRace.  aRacial Justice.  aReligion.  aRobert 